I think you are right...I'd just forgotten how animals do have a sense of fear or pain, related to their survival instinct.  And, of course, for domestic animals, after eons of interacting with humans, it has changed their overall instincts.   Your points are all very valid!<br>
(I'm not sure what tangent I was off on, in mind <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
Humans, being a composite of mineral,plant and animal kingdoms with that emotional and reasoning portion thrown in, really have a challenge, it seems.<br>
<br>
Do you feel that after an individual &quot;evolves&quot; to a certain point....or, becomes more aware....that they can move beyond that &quot;survival instinct&quot; mode?  When they can become of aware of what they &quot;REALLY&quot; are, universally?  seems that would tend to eliminate a lot of the fears.....the understanding that there really is no such thing as &quot;death&quot;?<br>
<br>
What are your (and others) thoughts on that?<br>
<br>
